-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stock Report: Afribank, Big Treat, Equity Bank, Eveready
-- Vincent Nwanma
-- 2010-04-23T15:10:12Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-04-23/sub-sahara-africa-stock-report-afribank-big-treat-equity-bank-eveready.html

          
          
             The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index declined for a fourth day, dropping 0.3 percent to
27,400.21 at the close in Lagos.  
 Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index increased for a fourth day,
climbing 0.2 percent to close at 1,687.08, raising the increase
this week to 1 percent.  
 Kenya’s All-Share Index rose 0.4 percent to 70.89 at the
close in Nairobi, a third day of gains.  
 Namibia’s FTSE/Namibia Overall Index declined for a third
day, falling less than 0.1 percent to 815.50 in the capital,
Windhoek.  
 The Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index extended a seven-
month high, rising 2 percent to 6,442.3 at the close in the
capital, Accra, the biggest five-day gain in seven weeks.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 Afribank Nigeria Plc (AFRIBANK NL) declined 13 kobo, or 4.7
percent to 2.61 naira after ThisDay newspaper reported Chairman
Osa Osunde and six others had been arrested for granting loans
without central-bank approval. The stock’s drop pares the gain
this year to 2.4 percent.  
 Big Treat Plc (BIGTREAT NL), a Nigerian baker and bread
retailer, declined 5 kobo, or 4.8 percent, to 1 naira after
reporting a loss for the nine months through September 2009. The
stock has increased 58 percent this year.  
 Equity Bank Ltd. (EQBNK KN), Kenya’s largest provider of
small loans, increased the most in 12 days, rising 45 cents, or
2.5 percent, to 18.40 shillings. The company reported a 36
percent advance in profit for the first quarter through March.  
 Eveready East Africa Ltd. (EVRD KN), surged 25 cents, or
5.8 percent, to 4.6 shillings, the biggest gain in two weeks.
The dry-cell battery manufacturer said profit for the first half
through March increased to 12.8 million shillings ($165,300)
from 290,000 shillings a year earlier after the company cut its
overhead and financing costs.  
